sns.pairplot(df[['Age', 'Fare', 'Survived', 'Pclass']], hue='Survived')
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.heatmap(df[['Age', 'Fare', 'SibSp', 'Parch', 'Survived', 'Pclass']].corr(), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm')
plt.show()
In [ ]:
OBSERVATIONS:

Pairplot:

Younger passengers (especially children) had a higher survival rate.

Higher Fare is associated with higher survival rates, likely due to higher-class passengers.

Heatmap:

Fare and Pclass are negatively correlated (-0.55), indicating higher fares for lower class numbers (1st class).

Survived shows mild positive correlation with Fare (0.26) and negative with Pclass (-0.34).
In [ ]:
 RELATIONSHIPS AND TRENDS:
    
Class and Survival: 1st class passengers had higher survival rates.

Gender and Survival: Females survived more than males.

Age and Survival: Children under 10 had higher survival rates.

Fare and Survival: Higher fares correlated with better survival chances.

SUMMARY OF FINDINGS

Demographics:

Majority of passengers were aged 20-40.

More males than females onboard.

Survival Trends:

Class: 1st class passengers had the highest survival rate (62%), while 3rd class had the lowest (24%).

Gender: 74% of females survived vs. 19% of males.

Age: Children (<10) and elderly (>60) had higher survival rates.

Fare: Higher fares correlated with better survival, likely due to class priority.

Correlations:

Pclass and Fare are strongly correlated with survival.

Age and SibSp/Parch showed weaker correlations.

Conclusion: Survival on the Titanic was significantly influenced by socio-economic factors (class, fare) and gender, with women and higher-class passengers having a clear advantage. Age also played a role, with children prioritized during evacuations.
